column168: On May 6, 2020 at 0956 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal NAT notified ERTS of a UN1993 Flammable liquid release from (2) 55 gallon poly drums. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all on site cleanup activities. At 1157 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed the release of approximately 1 quart from the drums due to punctures caused by nails on the pallet. Contractors over packed the damaged drums into their own 85 gallon poly drums along with all cleanup debris. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

Company vehicle was travelling east on Old Mt Holly Rd in its lane of travel.  V2 was travelling west and crossed the center line, striking the Company vehicle in its power unit fuel tank.  V2 driver admitted to being distracted.  The collision resulted in the fuel tank rupturing and spilling.  Absorbent and booms were placed immediately to contain the diesel from the fuel tank.  STAT Environmental responded immediately along with Charlotte Fire Dept.

column168: While the driver was unloading fuel, the hose from the maniflod ruptured. The driver immediately shut down the pump but did not drain the manifold or hose. When he pulled away from the site (turning Right onto the roadway) the fuel left the hose and maniflod contacting the roadway.   The release lasted a matter of seconds. The driver recognized the fuel leaving the pump compartment and immediately stopped his travel and spread dirt on the fuel and called his supervisor.   Upon using dirt to soak up the diesel fuel a street sweeper was dispatched to the scene and proceeded to capture the contaminated soil. A large plastic tarp was place on the shoulder of the road and then the material was placed on it. The next day the "pile" of soil was taken to a facility that is permitted to dispose of contaminated soil. The soil was run through an incenerator.   No further action taken.
column169: Instructed all drivers to halt deliveries and completely shut down in the event of a mechanical failure. Retrace steps to ensure any release is immediately mitigated,. (Turn off pump, drain hose, drain manifold and use absorbant cloth / dry sweep when needed). This incident was an anomaly. The hose blowing at the manifold could not have been forseen.

column168: GATX18644 is the lead car in a GATX Tank Train that was found in the CP Rail Saratoga Yard actively venting liquid gasoline from the Pressure Relief Device (PRD) and dripping from the bottom outlet valve plug.  Yard crews immediately placed absorbent pads under the car and notified Railroad HazMat Response Officer (HazMat).  Upon arrival of HazMat, car was still venting, pressure reading on the car was 90-psi. A Haz-Hammock was set up in addition to the absorbents for product containment.  A vacuum truck was mobilized to the site and a 2" chemical transfer hose was attached from the cam fitting on the manway and run to the vacuum truck.  The vacuum truck was opened, but no vacuum applied, the tank car valve was opened and the pressure differential moved the product to the vacuum truck.  This relived the pressure on the car and with the removal of pressure and product the car stopped venting thru the PRD.  This process was continued until the product was below the manway opening in the car (visually checked thru the cam valve on the manway).  Once product was below the manway, the manway was opened and outage taken showing that the car was shell full.  Stenciling on the car indicated that 10.5" = 4% tank outage.  A clean stinger was utilized and removed an estimated 1,437-gallons of product to allow proper outage in the car. The BOV was still dripping after relieving the pressure on the car and believed that the pressure had pushed product into the ball valve.  The valve was cycled twice, the plug removed, cleaned and replaced the plug which stopped the leak. The car pressures were checked in the remaining cars of the tank train with all within normal limits.  GATX18644 was sealed and cleared for continued shipment to destination. Estimated 5-gallons released to containment.
column169: Upon additional investigation at a latter date, it was determined that the cars in the Tank-Train were not equalized.  Shippers should confirm outages prior to shipment.

EQ Industrial Services, Inc. delivered 13 chromic acid tank bottom drums from Scot Industries to Envirite of Illinois. While attempting to offload, it was discovered that one drum of chromic acid tank bottoms was not properly secured and had tipped onto its side. When the driver attempted to reposition the drum, the lid loosened. Approximately 5-7 gallons of hazardous material leaked out of the package onto the truck floor and deck plate. The truck was positioned within the sump area and all hazardous material was captured. There was no release of hazardous material to the environment.    Envirite operational personnel immediately contained the spill, cleaned the sump, and containerized the rinse waters in a 300-gallon tote. Five drums were placed in overpack containment due to being covered in waste. All containers were labeled, characterized, and will be properly disposed of at Envirite.     The packages failed in transportation due to the following factors:   -The generator did not utilize a package that was rated for liquids.    -The drum was not adequately secured while in transportation.
column169: Transporter is reinforcing proper container selection with the generator. Refresher training is being conducted for EQ Industrial Service, Inc. drivers on proper container selection, load securement, and Stop Work Authority.

At the of pump transfer via CMV pump to Customer tank, product began to overflow from top of customer's tank. Driver immediately shut-off pump and upon further investigation, it was discovered that the customer miscalculated the amount of product in their tank prior to the start of transfer resulting in approximately 50 gallon spill into and outside of containment area. While customer was cleaning up spill, driver was unhooking transfer lines from CMV pump and product splashed onto his chemical gloves, front of shirt and front of paints. Driver went immediately to on-site safety showing, rinsed & changed clothing. Product did not make direct contact with driver's skin, therefore, first-aid/treatment was not needed.    Due to driver being a Texas based employee, Carrier policy required driver to be sent for Post Incident testing and evaluation. Driver was sent to On-Site Medical-Gonzales, LA. on 5-13-20 and during evaluation, driver indicated that he may have inhaled some of the chemical. On-Site completed evaluation and required the driver to return for a follow-up on 5-14-20. Driver returned on 5-14-20 as scheduled and was cleared by On-Site to return to full-duty.
column169: Driver verbally counselled by Carrier Safety Dept. personnel concerning proper hose handling per Carrier policy and procedure.   Shipper conducted fact finding investigation via webinar with Customer and Carrier on 5-15-20. Conclusion of findings and corrective action was to have Customer replace level gauge on Customer's tank to ensure accurate readings for future deliveries.

column168: On 05/04/2020, JBHU 312383 was reported leaking by BNSF personnel upon deramp at the BNSF San Bernardino IMF. The waybill lists the unit as carrying hazardous material. In the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold and moved to the containment pit pending interior inspection.  Premium Environmental was contacted and Patriot Environmental Services was dispatched to remediate the load. Interior inspection revealed palletized stretched wrapped boxes paint stowed 2 high and 2 wide with no doorway securement. The leaking substance was deemed as hazardous by Patriot. The origin of the leak was boxes on the bottom of a bottom pallet. The weight of the top pallet caused the boxes to collapse, which caused about 11 gallons of product to leak out with about 4 gallons reaching the ground. This incident has been deemed as shipper   s responsibility and all contractor cost from Patriot Environmental Services will be recharged to JB Hunt.

The crash took place on interstate 10 @ mile-marker 99 in Louisiana just outside of Lafayette city limits. The unit was completely on its side, laying on side of the interstate in a shallow ditch. There was a small leak of product dripping from the vapor release valve on top of the trailer. This was due to the weight of the product pushing against the valve. The entire unit has damage to the entire right side. It is too early to tell if the barrel of the trailer was damaged. It had been raining so the interstate as well as the shoulder was soaked with rainwater. There were no evacuations ordered and know exposures reported. The state closed the east bound side of the interstate until the wreckage was completely cleared.
column169: Highway Transport requires our drivers to stop in a safe location every three hours for what we title as a “Tire Check.” This was implemented so that our drivers can ensure everything is okay with the units and the load; leaks, placards, tires not over heating/flat, lights working and for the driver to get a little exercise by walking around the entire unit. Highway will be monitoring this policy more aggressively to make sure that we as a company are and will continue to operate in a very safe manner.

Subject tank car, GAPX 9000, loaded with sodium hydroxide was placed in a train at Calvert City, KY and arrived at Paducah Yard for classification at approximately 1830 on May 27, 2020.  At approximately 2303 on May 27, 2020 a car man on duty in Paducah yard noticed a steady drip from the bottom outlet valve.  The carman followed procedure and notified the dispatcher.  The dispatcher began notifications of company personnel as well as NRC and Chemtrec.  Westlake (shipper) was notified and responded and was able to stop the leak by tightening the bottom outlet valve.  The valve was found to be "tool tight" but still allowing a leak.  This was found to be the cars first loading after re qualification.

column168: GATX18647 was the second car in a GATX Tank-Train.  Railroad personnel viewed liquid product being released from the pressure relief device (PRD), placed absorbent pads under the car and made notification to Railroad Hazardous Materials (Hazmat) Officer.  Hazmat responded with outside contractors to the site. Initial pressure on the car was 80-psi.  Upon arrival of a vacuum truck, a chemical hose was attached to the cam fitting on the manway lid, run to the vacuum truck and the vacuum truck valve opened.  The manway valve was opened and the pressure differential pushed the product to the vacuum truck.  This stopped the release from the PRD.  Once the product level was below the manway (viewed thru the valve) the manway was opened and outage obtained.  Stenciling on the car indicates that 10.5" = 4% outage in the tank.  The car was shell full and an estimated 1,437-gallons of product was removed from the tank car to allow proper outage for shipment.  Due to the fact that car was in a Tank-Train and this was the second NAR from this string of cars, all of the cars in the string were opened and outages checked before releasing the cars for movement.
column169: Upon investigation, it was noted that the first two cars in the Tank-Car string were shell full, cars 3 & 4 were slightly over the outage limit, cars 5 & 6 had proper outage and car 7, the last car had 45" of outage.  It was concluded that the cars were not allowed to properly equalize prior to closing the connecting valves in the Tank-Train.  Shippers should verify proper outages on each car prior to shipment.

column168: Veolia employees determined that the 55-gallon drum was leaking while off-loading a truck at Veolia's 10 day in-transit facility in Kenmore, NY. Approximately 1 pint of material leaked from the container. Upon inspection it was identified that there was a small puncture at the top,  side of drum (about three inches from the top of the drum).   There are two causes to the release that occurred. 1) The drum appears to have had some  corrosion caused by the material within the drum. The drum showed signs of rust from within the  drum after the puncture occurred. 2) The drum was also punctured by a metal "s" hook that was in the truck's e-track load securement system. The "s" hook pierced the drum when it was loaded into the back of the vehicle. The Veolia employee did not see the protruding "s" hook when he loaded  the drum into the truck.  Veolia, Tonawanda, NY employees donned the appropriate PPE, overpacked the leaking container  and cleaned up the spill.
column169: Veolia, Tonawanda, NY employees had a meeting with the Veolia EH&S manager about assuring no  sharp objects were within any vehicles. Veolia employees need to be aware of potential sources of  drum punctures when loading containers into the truck and remove them. All employees will be  retrained on checking vehicles for potential sharp objects. The customer (offeror) was notified of the  spill and the integrity issue of the drum. They are being asked to check on the quality of the drums  they are using and to assure that chemicals are not incompatible with the containers.

During transfer of product via CMV air compressor to customer storage tank, product began overflowing from top of customer storage tank. Driver immediately stopped transfer procedure and upon further investigation, it was discovered that customer miscalculated level of product prior to start of transfer resulting in a 60 gallon spill into containment area.   Spill was cleaned up by customer and investigation continued. At conclusion of investigation, it was discovered that the customer storage tank did not have a level gauge installed and employees were required to "visually" estimate the tank level prior to delivery of new product.
column169: Deliveries to customer storage tank were suspended until a digital leveling gauge was installed and customer employees were trained on proper operation of gauge.

I THEN PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE PACKAGE TO DETERMINE WHETHER THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN LEAKED ON OR WAS LEAKING. I DISCOVERED THAT THE BOTTLE CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS LIQUID HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE. On Saturday May 30, 2020 at approximate 1930 a driver arrived with documents for 081-49131036.  Documents contained the IAC, air waybill and invoice.  After Agent Gabby Rosales processed security paperwork, the driver presented shipment for dock acceptance.    During dock acceptance Noberto Duque discovered a clear envelope sleeve containing a Shippers Declaration.  Noberto immediately flagged the shipment and brought it to the attention of Supervisor Kelly Covarrubias.  The shipment had a Shipper’s Declaration but no hazard labels or statement on the air waybill indicating the same.  As a Category 6 trained person Kelly recognized the mismatch of Shipper’s Declaration to labels.  Kelly also recognized that that an air waybill description of “aircraft parts” could indicate the presence of a hidden dangerous good as outlined in IATA DGR 2.2.  With aim of preventing undeclared dangerous goods from being transported and given the high visibility for this AOG must-ride shipment on the booking list we attempted to discern if this was indeed a dangerous good.    We enlisted CAP018 to obtain a contact for this air waybill and contacted Terri who is listed as point of contact in the remarks section, multiple calls resulted in voicemail.  We dialed the listed number on the top right of CAP018 and were unable to reach a contact.  We then found, in an email thread, a contact for the Schenker AOG desk that is monitored on a 24/7 basis (866-890-1235) and spoke to Diane.  We explained the shipment arrived with a Shippers Declaration but lacked hazard labels.  Diane confirmed it was not a dangerous good and granted permission to remove the declaration.  Shipment was then loaded and manifested on QF0940/30May 2020.
column169: A read and sign will be issued to all staff to advise when suspicion arises that a shipment may contain dangerous goods the shipment will be placed on hold (regardless of commodity or booking level).  Qantas customer service will obtain written confirmation from the ultimate shipper, not the Forwarder.  The Forwarder will then confirm by endorsement of the air waybill that no part of the content is dangerous (e.g. “Not-Restricted”).

THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A CORRUGATED DIVIDER AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 44 LBS PER SQ IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column168: On 5/27/2020, at 2158 hours, personnel on the CSXT Industrial Lead to the Consignee's Facility discovered TILX 191862, a loaded tank car of Butyraldehyde, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2020-0527-00343). Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 2 of 4 liquid line flange to fittings plate securement bolts less than tool tight, resulting in a Non-Accident Release. Additionally, the liquid line valve into the threaded connection was easily spun, and the vapor line valve into its threaded connection was easily spun. The vapor line valve secondary closure plug was also less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Kendrick Bowen, phone 214-577-1046. Contractor personnel secured all loose service equipment and cleaned all impacted surfaces. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 284 NARRI: 80

Our driver was delivering Clear Diesel into the City of Early's 500 Gallon Clear Diesel tank. After the driver started unloading the fuel , he stepped up on the truck steps to lean into his cab. He heard an explosion and turned to his left to see what happened.  The fuel tank he was delivering the fuel into had exploded and fire was engulfing our driver .  Our driver ran through the fire escape He sustained burns to his left arm  and left torso. Our driver ran into the building where the Early Fire Department is located, the tank is located directly behind the Early FD. column168: Driver returned from Vorteq Coil Finishers in Valencia, PA. As driver was unloading a roll-off box containing inorganic hazardous waste F019 Sludge at the Envirite of Ohio Hazardous Waste Storage Pad #2, free liquid spilled over the tailgate and onto the storage pad and asphalt in front of the pad. The driver was unaware the box contained free liquid.  The spill was immediately contained and absorbed with oil dry and was not released to the environment.
column169: Driver was unaware roll-off box contained free liquid.  As a matter of policy going forward, drivers must inspect every roll-off box to ensure no free liquids exist and photograph the contents of the roll-off box before pick-up at customer sites. This means removing the tarp or lid to inspect the load entirely from front to back, side to side and each corner. Also, if there are any indicators during transportation pointing to the existence of free liquids (such as surging/sloshing) that may accumulate during transit due to sheer thinning properties of the sludge, the driver must pull off at the nearest safe stopping point to inspect. If free liquids are observed, call the transportation manager to determine next steps.

A FedEx Pak containing was observed to contain potentially undeclared DG at the origin station, FRGB, in Melville, NY. Following discovery of undeclared dangerous goods from the same distribution warehouse, FedEx Spill Cleanup staff discovered that the pak for this tracking number contained four plastic bottles of Leisure Time hot tub products including of Leisure Time Defender 32 oz, Leisure Time Foam Down 16 oz, Leisure Time Enzyme 32 oz and Leisure Time Bright and Clear 32 oz. Per the associated SDS Leisure Time Defender is classified as UN3267, Corrosive liquid, basic, organic, n.o.s. which is a class 8 Corrosive Packing Group II. The other commodities are NONDG. There were no Dangerous Goods markings or labels on the FedEx Pak, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: GATX 209832 was found leaking with product crystallized around the bottom outlet valve. Upon investigation the UPRR HMM found that there was crystallized product in the bottom outlet valve cap between the gasket and the valve which was not allowing a proper seal. After further investigation it was found that there was crystallized product around the bottom outlet valve ball which was not allowing the valve to close completely.
column169: The UPRR HMM actuated the bottom outlet valve and the valve sealed correctly after it was closed successfully stopping the leak. The HMM then chipped the solid product out of the bottom outlet cap to free the gasket the secured the bottom outlet valve cap and successfully secured the car. The HMM then waited 20 minutes and no leaks were observed and GATX 209832 was released for movement to destination.

column168: On Tuesday, May 26, 2020, Lykins Transportation, Inc. (LTI) driver was operating a straight truck tanker. Driver was headed east bound on St Rt 350 enroute to Clarksville, OH loaded with approximately 1,108 gallons of dyed diesel, 900 gallons of clear diesel, and 650 gallons of unleaded gasoline. The driver had never been on that road prior to that day. He was covering for another driver in the Lebanon, OH area. Therefore, the driver was not familiar with the route and was using GPS which took the driver on St Rt 350 headed to Clarksville, OH from Monroe, OH. Parts of St Rt 350 in that area are steep and curvy. The driver should have not been on that section of the state route and was going too fast for the road. At approximately 0815 the driver was approaching a sharp downhill curve and failed to control the tanker which resulted in a rollover striking a tree and went into a ravine with a creek bottom adjacent to the road. The driver was able to climb out of the truck cab. The tanker suffered compartmental/piping damage which resulted in a spill. Approximately 350 gallons of diesel was released into the creek which is a tributary to the Little Miami River. Most of the product was contained to the tributary. Some of the release did enter the Little Miami River, but the amount is unknown. No gasoline was released only diesel.  Multiple first responders and hazardous material cleanup crews responded to the scene. Initially, the spill was mitigated with the use of oil absorbent booms and pads. And, a large boom was placed in the Little Miami River at the base of the creek. Also, on May 27th several thousand gallons of water was flushed down the creek and captured to recovery the bulk of the diesel in the creek. Over the next few weeks spill absorbent booms and pads were maintained throughout the tributary along with the large boom in the river. As rainfall events occurred, diesel was absorbed, and supplies were replaced as needed. As of today, the clean up still under way as the site and it is waiting for a few more good rainfall events to capture any remaining diesel that is still left behind. The site is monitored during and after rainfall events. The cleanup will be completed in the next few weeks depending on the weather.
column169: Lykins Transportation, Inc. (LTI) reviews all incidents, in order, to determine the root cause, preventability, and what actions, i.e. training or procedures, need to be conducted or implemented so that the incident will not happen again. The rollover was caused by the driver being unfamiliar with the area and going to fast for the condition of the roadway. LTI conducts multiple driver focused safety meetings during the year. LTI will brief all drivers about the incident and its preventability. LTI will focus on the importance of communicating to drivers where impassable routes are located and best practices when covering unknown areas.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling, driver struck a vehicle in front of him, lost control and veered into the center median of the Highway. As a result, the trailer was damaged and caused cargo to shift. The Local Fire Department, Grant County EMA, Wisconsin DOT, and Tegeler Wrecker responded to assess the site. Tegeler Wrecker assisted in recovery efforts, applied absorbent material to the affected roadway and cleared debris from the road. Enviromark was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, two 330-gallon totes were discovered damaged. Enviromark pumped approximately 40 gallons of free product from within the totes, and estimated 620 gallons had released to the asphalt roadway and grassy soil within the median. Once Tegeler cleared the road, tote was offloaded and site secured, Enviromark marked the area of impact within the median. A third party consultant was contacted to perform final site remediation, which was coordinated with North Shore Environmental.
column169: N&M Transfer will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

EMI then contacted local subcontractor, Enhanced Environmental and Emergency Services(3E) and they responded to the terminal. The drums were removed from the van until the one Ieaking was identified. This drum was placed into an 85-gallon steel overpack and properly labeled. The wooden floor was wiped up and the underneath of the van was also wiped. The steel overpack remained on the van and the earlier mentioned drums were reloaded. The bottom chime of the drum had released the material. No mechanical damage was observed. The drum leaked because of vibration during the transport phase. Length of release was estimated at four to five hours.

column168: On May 28,2020, at approximately 12:00 p.m. CDT, personnel at the above-referenced facility owned by R+L Carriers(RLC) discovered one(1) 275-gallon poly tote of an ethanol solution (UN1170) had been damaged by a load strap while secured in a trailer. As a result, approximately five(5) gallons of an ethanol solution was released to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC((DES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental(HCE) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, HCE personnel noted approximately five(5) gallons of ethanol solution had released to the trailer floor but had evaporated, requiring no additional remediation to the trailer interior. HCE personnel then gravity fed the ethanol solution from the one(1) damaged 275-gallon poly tote into a new 275-gallon poly tote. The 275-gallon tote of ethanol solution was then left with facility personnel for reuse. The one(1) damaged 275-gallon tote was collected by HCE personnel for transport and disposal as non-hazardous. HCE personnel secured the site and demobilized.

column168: At approximately 9:25 a.m. on May 29, 2020, a dump truck hauling approximately 30 cubic yards of stabilized wastes and microencapsulated debris from Heritage Environmental Services, LLC located in Indianapolis, Indiana (“Heritage”) caught fire in the bed of the vehicle.  The driver pulled the truck over to the side of the road and a bystander called 911.  The Danville Fire Department (DFD) arrived on scene and quickly extinguished the fire.   The water used to extinguish the fire contacted the material in the truck.  Some of the water was absorbed into the material and the majority of the remaining water was captured into the spill containment that the fire department placed at the tail gate of the dump truck.  A small amount made its way on to the ground around the truck.  The fire department successfully used clay absorbent and pigs to create a dike to prevent the water from entering any ravines or waterways.  The incident occurred near the intersection of US 36 and Clear Creek Drive in Danville, Indiana.
column169: As the party that shipped the material, Heritage Environmental Services plans to monitor the temperature of materials that contain the wastestreams that were involved in the fire for a period of time before they are loaded to ensure excessive heat is not being generated prior to shipment.  This procedure will be used to confirm the material is safe to transport.

column168: The decision to refill the tank as need at Shore Point Distributors is at the discretion of globe Petroleum, Inc. On Wednesday , May 27th, 2020, Globe Petroleum had a company driver look at the on-site tank gauge located on the tank to determine what amount of product Diesel Fuel was in the tank was misread , the actual amount that was in the tank was greater than originally reported . On Thursday , May 28th, the dispatch office at Globe Petroleum , Inc. authorized the delivery driver to load 7,000 gallons of on road ULSD fuel based on incorrect information . Upon arrival at the customers location Shore Point Distributors with the on road ULSD Fuel, The deliver driver did not reconfirm the amount of on road ULSD Fuel in the tank before he started the transfer of product from his tanker to the onsite  10,000 gallon tank . Due to this oversite , a release of ULSD Fuel from the overfill on the tank occurred. An estimate of fuel released was approximately between 40-60 Gallons of ULSD Fuel. Some of the released fuel was captured in the tanks containment unit and the balance was released on the ground surrounding the tank. The delivery driver immediately began containment procedures to mitigate the spread of the release. After he contained the spill, he informed the Dispatch office at Globe Petroleum, Inc. of what happened, and a spill response team was dispatched to the scene. In total it took six (6) bags of oil absorbent "Speedy Dry" to remediate the released ULSD Fuel on the ground surrounding the tank and the remaining released fuel in the containment area is being scheduled for removal by LORCO Inc. via a Vac -Truck.
column169: Upon a complete investigation into the events leading up to and including remediation of the above release, Globe Pertoleum, Inc. has determined that even though incorrect information was communicated, Ultimately it is the responsibility of the delivery driver to confirm how much product is in a tank before the process of fuel transfer begins. These steadfast procedures used as an example as to why it is imperative to follow the strict guidelines of loading and unload procedures as a Deliver Driver.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis
